1
00:00:02,242 --> 00:00:06,046
Tonight I'd like to discuss the Sutta titled The Honey Ball.

2
00:00:07,248 --> 00:00:13,316
In parts of India, cakes baked from flour and honey and oil are still called honey balls.

3
00:00:14,776 --> 00:00:24,910
When Ananda, the Buddha's cousin and attendant, heard the discourse, he said it satisfied a spiritual seeker in the way a honey ball satisfies a famished man.

4
00:00:26,190 --> 00:00:30,797
So what we're getting tonight is some high calorie spiritual nourishment.

5
00:00:34,017 --> 00:00:41,826
Now high calorie foods can also be heavy going on the system and I'd certainly rank this Sutta as a difficult one to digest.

6
00:00:43,368 --> 00:00:51,598
Even in the original story, as you will see, the Buddha's disciples need three separate attempts to explain the matter before the penny drops.

7
00:00:53,521 --> 00:00:58,927
Let's go through all three levels of explanation before looking at any one of them in detail.

8
00:01:01,152 --> 00:01:05,000
It all starts with the Buddha going into a wood for his days abiding.

9
00:01:06,483 --> 00:01:16,924
A man named Dandapani is walking in the woods and seeing the Buddha approaches him and asks about his spiritual beliefs and practice.

10
00:01:16,944 --> 00:01:18,147
The Buddha replies,

11
00:01:19,849 --> 00:01:34,938
Friend, I assert and proclaim a teaching such that one does not quarrel with anyone in the world with its gods, its Maras and its Brahmas, in this generation with its recluses and Brahmins, its princes and its people.

12
00:01:34,918 --> 00:01:50,397
a teaching such that perceptions no more underlie that brahmin who abides detached from sensual pleasures without perplexity shorn of worry free from craving for any kind of being

13
00:01:52,941 --> 00:02:06,917
In many of the suttas, the Buddha finds the exact teaching needed for whoever he is talking to, and that person becomes completely enlightened, though we 21st century seekers might be baffled by the Buddha's words.

14
00:02:08,264 --> 00:02:24,109
But Dandapani seems as perplexed as us modern-day dullards, and is described as shaking his head, wagging his tongue, and raising his eyebrows till his forehead was puckered into three lines, after which he departed, leaning on his stick.

15
00:02:26,171 --> 00:02:32,701
As an aside, Dandapani wasn't a recluse, and was just wandering round the wood for exercise.

16
00:02:33,052 --> 00:02:39,021
Perhaps the Buddha's response irritated Dandapani enough to spur a spiritual quest at some later stage.

17
00:02:40,663 --> 00:02:52,181
One way or another Dandapani departs in a huff and the Buddha settles back to his meditation for the afternoon before later rejoining his disciples and telling them about his exchange with Dandapani.

18
00:02:53,424 --> 00:03:01,034
It seems the disciples were also puzzled by this summary of the Dhamma and one of them basically asked the Buddha what he is talking about.

19
00:03:01,807 --> 00:03:04,110
So the Buddha offers this explanation.

20
00:03:06,073 --> 00:03:13,800
Bhikkhu, as to the source by which perceptions and notions tinged by mental proliferation beset a man.

21
00:03:15,323 --> 00:03:29,419
If nothing is found there to delight in, welcome and hold to, this is the end of the underlying tendency to lust, of the underlying tendency to aversion, of the underlying tendency to views,

22
00:03:29,719 --> 00:03:42,733
of the underlying tendency to doubt, of the underlying tendency to conceit, of the underlying tendency to desire for being, of the underlying tendency to ignorance.

23
00:03:44,375 --> 00:03:53,544
This is the end of resorting to rods and weapons, of quarrels, brawls, disputes, recrimination, malice and false speech.

24
00:03:54,626 --> 00:03:58,949
Here these evil, unwholesome states cease without remainder.

25
00:04:01,478 --> 00:04:06,426
Having said this much, the Buddha then leaves his disciples and retires into his dwelling.

26
00:04:09,072 --> 00:04:20,752
I imagine you will be relieved to hear that this explanation hasn't done much to satisfy the disciples, who then go to seek out a senior teacher to pick out the meaning of the Buddha's words.

27
00:04:21,711 --> 00:04:35,954
They chose Mahakakana, who at first demurs, saying that they should have asked the Buddha, whom he likens to heartwood in the tree of Dhamma, while he, Mahakakana, represents only the branches and leaves of that tree.

28
00:04:37,154 --> 00:04:42,202
But after a bit of persuasion, he agrees to give them his interpretation, which goes like this.

29
00:04:44,706 --> 00:04:49,473
Dependent on the I and forms, I-consciousness arises.

30
00:04:50,483 --> 00:04:54,269
The meeting of the three is called contact.

31
00:04:54,290 --> 00:04:56,913
With contact as condition there is feeling.

32
00:04:58,456 --> 00:05:01,322
What one feels that one perceives.

33
00:05:02,884 --> 00:05:06,190
What one perceives that one thinks about.

34
00:05:06,230 --> 00:05:11,901
What one thinks about that one mentally proliferates.

35
00:05:13,062 --> 00:05:28,084
with what one has mentally proliferated as the source perceptions and notions tinged by mental proliferation beset a man with respect to past, future and present forms cognizable through the eye.

36
00:05:30,767 --> 00:05:40,841
He goes on to say the same about all the other sense doors hearing, tasting, smelling, body sensations and mind objects such as thoughts and perceptions.

37
00:05:41,901 --> 00:05:52,940
He then continues When there is the I of form and I consciousness it is possible to point out the manifestation of contact.

38
00:05:54,237 --> 00:06:00,283
When there is the manifestation of contact it is possible to point out the manifestation of feeling.

39
00:06:01,423 --> 00:06:14,916
And so on until When there is the manifestation of thinking it is possible to point out the manifestation of being beset by perceptions and notions tinged by mental proliferation.

40
00:06:17,480 --> 00:06:22,944
Likewise he says the same about all the other sense doors and then concludes with

41
00:06:24,375 --> 00:06:33,105
When there is no I, no form, and no I-consciousness, it is impossible to point out the manifestation of contact.

42
00:06:34,387 --> 00:06:48,002
And so on until, when there is no manifestation of thinking, it is impossible to point out the manifestation of being beset by perceptions and notions tinged by mental proliferation.

43
00:06:49,523 --> 00:06:52,846
And as usual, he says the same about all the other sense doors.

44
00:06:54,160 --> 00:06:58,526
This, I'm sorry to have to tell you, is the end of the line as regards explanations.

45
00:06:59,247 --> 00:07:02,973
The Bhikkhus, we are told, were delighted with Mahakakana's words.

46
00:07:04,596 --> 00:07:08,781
But they went and checked them with the Buddha as Mahakakana himself advised them to do.

47
00:07:10,064 --> 00:07:16,894
The Buddha praises Mahakakana and says he would have said exactly the same thing if he had been pressed for a further explanation.

48
00:07:18,511 --> 00:07:32,869
It's at this point that Ananda describes the Sutta in terms of a honeyball, saying, Just as if a man exhausted by hunger and weakness comes upon a honeyball, in the course of eating it would find a sweet, delectable flavour.

49
00:07:33,990 --> 00:07:45,564
So too, Venerable Sir, any able-minded bhikkhu, in the course of scrutinising with wisdom the meaning of this discourse on the Dhamma, would find satisfaction and confidence of mind.

50
00:07:47,552 --> 00:07:54,788
The Buddha seems pleased with Ananda's analogy and tells the assembly they should remember this discourse as the honey ball.

51
00:07:56,651 --> 00:08:04,127
So let's nibble our way through the honey ball and see can we detect any of the sweet delectable flavour that Ananda found here.

52
00:08:06,014 --> 00:08:18,932
First, we have the Buddha's synopsis of the Dhamma for Dandapani which starts with the description of a world without conflict and follows with the description of being free from attachments with their burden of worry and strife.

53
00:08:21,235 --> 00:08:30,148
He describes freedom as a state where perceptions no longer underlie that Brahmin who abides detached from sensual pleasures.

54
00:08:32,187 --> 00:08:40,456
He is linking internal and external conflict with being attached to and somehow founded upon our perceptions.

55
00:08:41,758 --> 00:08:48,024
His Dhamma, he declares, cuts through all that so that we find ourselves at peace with the world.

56
00:08:52,369 --> 00:08:56,394
He describes this peace as applying to the worldly level of princes and men.

57
00:08:57,634 --> 00:09:00,118
All our worldly concerns fade away.

58
00:09:00,942 --> 00:09:04,826
we are also at peace with the heavenly realm of gods and the hell realm of Mara.

59
00:09:06,366 --> 00:09:12,732
In an age so dominated by science and technology, it's not easy for us to think of heaven and hell realms.

60
00:09:13,854 --> 00:09:19,980
Instead, we can think of these as temporary mind states, heavenly bliss and hellish rage.

61
00:09:21,260 --> 00:09:29,008
We no longer quarrel with whatever we come up against in the external world or in any of the internal worlds we experience within our minds.

62
00:09:31,908 --> 00:09:36,937
I don't think any of us would quarrel with the notion of inner peace and making peace with the world.

63
00:09:37,999 --> 00:09:55,991
It's the phrase, Perceptions no longer underlie that Brahmin who abides non-attached to sensual pleasures, which stumps us, and like Dandapani, be causing our brows to furrow into the three lines and tempting us to stomp off.

64
00:09:58,131 --> 00:10:06,479
And sure enough, when his disciples ask the Buddha to explain himself, he expands on the issue of perception and how they can lead to grief.

65
00:10:08,600 --> 00:10:13,885
Perception, if you remember, are the labels we place on whatever sense data comes to us.

66
00:10:15,927 --> 00:10:27,278
If our eye falls on some green grass, our mind sorts through its memories of stuff that is shaped and coloured like this and comes up with perceptions green and grass.

67
00:10:28,490 --> 00:10:36,538
we might then quietly add a perception like unimportant, as we move on to label the next bit of incoming sense data.

68
00:10:38,879 --> 00:10:53,693
In this explanation of his message to Dandapani, the Buddha basically says that if only we can stop delighting in the source of perceptions that beset us, then we'd be freed from underlying tendencies to lust and other afflictions.

69
00:10:55,235 --> 00:10:56,876
There's a lot to think about here.

70
00:10:59,000 --> 00:11:03,645
He is saying that we delight in exactly that which is causing us to suffer.

71
00:11:04,707 --> 00:11:14,120
Although our perceptions beset us, cause us grief, the only reason they are doing that is because we delight in the source of these perceptions.

72
00:11:15,221 --> 00:11:16,663
We're in a mess, it seems.

73
00:11:19,407 --> 00:11:20,969
Let's look at a possible example.

74
00:11:22,270 --> 00:11:26,576
Suppose I'm fretting about my neighbour's dogs who I hear growling in her back garden.

75
00:11:27,586 --> 00:11:29,975
There may be many levels to the mental disturbance.

76
00:11:30,857 --> 00:11:39,469
Concern that the dogs might start fighting, grief at the thought that they are possibly being neglected, instinctive fear at the sound of growling.

77
00:11:40,140 --> 00:11:42,325
All of these can set off chains of thought.

78
00:11:43,287 --> 00:11:44,308
Is there going to be a fight?

79
00:11:44,789 --> 00:11:45,591
What should I do?

80
00:11:46,192 --> 00:11:46,975
Will I get hurt?

81
00:11:48,437 --> 00:11:51,462
Each of these thoughts involves a long string of perceptions.

82
00:11:52,686 --> 00:11:59,820
Even the basic sound had to be perceived as growling and with that perceptions like danger would have emerged.

83
00:12:01,251 --> 00:12:14,994
Although I'm getting stressed out by all my thoughts about the dogs and what might happen, the Buddha is saying that the only cause for my distress is that I'm delighting in, welcoming and holding on to the source of these perceptions.

84
00:12:17,258 --> 00:12:19,260
What is the source of these perceptions?

85
00:12:20,844 --> 00:12:26,753
This is the question that Mahakakana addresses when pressed for his understanding of the Buddha's words.

86
00:12:27,644 --> 00:12:38,701
he traces the source back to the moment of sense contact which involves in my case the sound of growling, the sense of hearing and the faculty of consciousness.

87
00:12:40,543 --> 00:12:45,572
If I'd been deaf or unconscious the doves could growl all they liked but I wouldn't be upset.

88
00:12:47,075 --> 00:12:52,342
But given those three conditions the growling sound made contact within my psyche.

89
00:12:53,904 --> 00:12:55,508
Mahakakana then says

90
00:12:56,399 --> 00:12:59,563
With contact as condition, there is feeling.

91
00:13:02,107 --> 00:13:04,312
We might think of feelings as purely physical.

92
00:13:05,232 --> 00:13:10,160
In my case, the growling might have impacted as a rough, low-pitched vibration on the eardrum.

93
00:13:11,562 --> 00:13:23,081
Although the sensations are physical, our mental system gets involved immediately, categorizing the sensation so as to work out whether it is a threat or an opportunity.

94
00:13:24,243 --> 00:13:29,148
This gives us a feeling for the sensation as pleasant, unpleasant or neutral.

95
00:13:30,450 --> 00:13:35,115
In the case of the growling dogs, my system feels the sound as unpleasant.

96
00:13:36,897 --> 00:13:41,861
Maha Kakana then says, What one feels, that one perceives.

97
00:13:44,024 --> 00:13:48,528
Many of those who have commented on this sutta note the grammatical change here.

98
00:13:49,251 --> 00:13:54,398
When describing the link between contact and feeling he used impersonal language.

99
00:13:55,438 --> 00:13:58,722
With contact as condition there is feeling.

100
00:14:00,384 --> 00:14:03,589
But this changes once perception comes into the picture.

101
00:14:04,690 --> 00:14:07,874
What one feels that one perceives.

102
00:14:09,434 --> 00:14:11,697
The language is now personal.

103
00:14:14,125 --> 00:14:25,996
This implies that the mind which categorises the sensation as growling also identifies itself as the one who feels this unpleasant sound and perceives it as growling.

104
00:14:27,158 --> 00:14:31,501
We have solidified both the external world and the internal world.

105
00:14:32,744 --> 00:14:39,070
We believe ourselves to be separate, a person who existed in the past and will exist in the future.

106
00:14:40,331 --> 00:14:55,315
Although Mahakakana doesn't spell out all the links independent origination for us, we can take it that we have at least gone through the links of desire and clinging when we form these perceptions based on feeling, to which he is referring here.

107
00:14:58,120 --> 00:15:03,488
Mahakakana's linking of perception and clinging is very interesting to reflect upon.

108
00:15:05,172 --> 00:15:11,966
The vibrations resonating on the eardrum are my only real point of contact with the external world.

109
00:15:13,951 --> 00:15:21,746
Once the mind puts the label growling on these vibrations, it can split itself off from the raw experience.

110
00:15:23,144 --> 00:15:35,782
Unless I can hold the label very lightly as a tentative possibility, needing constant reaffirmation from each new sound, my subjective experience freezes around the label.

111
00:15:37,403 --> 00:15:38,686
Fluidity is lost.

112
00:15:40,227 --> 00:15:50,383
A sense of self emerges in that abstract frozen world of this and that, me and you, growling and danger.

113
00:15:53,029 --> 00:16:04,082
If any of you have read Rob Barbie's book, Seeing That Freeze, you'll probably remember the strong emphasis Rob also gives to the link between perception and clinging.

114
00:16:06,004 --> 00:16:07,886
Say we're lost in a temper tantrum.

115
00:16:09,109 --> 00:16:14,514
Our sense of self is strong and our perception of our adversary hardens into enmity.

116
00:16:15,153 --> 00:16:24,408
Later, when we calm down, we no longer feel so identified with our view and might also start to see the other person in a kinder light.

117
00:16:26,172 --> 00:16:29,937
The perception of enmity fades as clinging is released.

118
00:16:31,048 --> 00:16:35,315
In general, Rob says, perceptions fade as clinging is released.

119
00:16:36,717 --> 00:16:42,626
This is a very useful phrase to contemplate and fits very neatly with Mahakakana's teaching.

120
00:16:43,587 --> 00:16:46,613
Perceptions fade as clinging is released.

121
00:16:49,356 --> 00:16:58,169
In the case of the growling dogs, we're seeing the opposite side of the coin, how perceptions and clinging get intertwined and lead to dukkha.

122
00:16:59,938 --> 00:17:06,953
Some innocuous vibrations on my eardrum have conjured up a sense of self around the perception, growling.

123
00:17:08,656 --> 00:17:19,720
The tendency then is to stop attending to the basic vibrations and instead to withdraw into an abstract internal world where my mind can build around that label.

124
00:17:21,386 --> 00:17:33,337
Many commentators say that there can be feedback loops within the 12-step process described by dependent origination, and we can see a perception-based feedback back loop here.

125
00:17:35,038 --> 00:17:40,006
The perception growling can now become a new input at the doorway of the mind.

126
00:17:41,147 --> 00:17:53,144
And if we attend to it, we have another sense contact which deepens the unpleasant feeling, tightens the clinging and goes on to generate another perception like danger.

127
00:17:53,204 --> 00:17:59,815
As Mahakakana says, what one perceives, that one thinks about.

128
00:18:02,258 --> 00:18:25,481
Thus my mind spins through a few feedback loops and finds the perception dog fits neatly alongside the perception growling and the perception neighbour's dogs fit with both until the jigsaw completes and the thought and image of the neighbour's dogs growling at one another establishes itself in my mind.

129
00:18:27,672 --> 00:18:29,154
Now there's nothing wrong with this.

130
00:18:30,096 --> 00:18:37,670
It's an aspect of human intelligence to be able to build a picture of what might be happening based on snippets of sensory information.

131
00:18:38,771 --> 00:18:42,397
The Buddha might have interpreted vibrations on his eardrum in a similar way.

132
00:18:43,720 --> 00:18:47,487
We need these interpretations in order to engage with the world.

133
00:18:48,547 --> 00:19:00,939
The only difference between the Buddha's approach and mine is that his piecing together of perceptions would have been done out of goodwill, as a deliberate, conscious decision to engage with the world.

134
00:19:02,280 --> 00:19:09,288
My picture, on the other hand, was built as an automatic reaction to unacknowledged aversion for the growling sound.

135
00:19:10,348 --> 00:19:14,772
Putting the pieces of the jigsaw together gives me the illusion of control.

136
00:19:16,491 --> 00:19:20,877
And my problem is that I get hooked on the jigsaw.

137
00:19:20,897 --> 00:19:25,163
I want to find new pieces to fit, see what new picture will emerge.

138
00:19:26,345 --> 00:19:35,037
It's this delight in jigsaw making which, according to the Buddha, keeps rekindling lust and aversion, which then underlie our quarrels with the world.

139
00:19:37,179 --> 00:19:43,748
In Mahakakana's words, what one thinks about, that one mentally proliferates.

140
00:19:44,942 --> 00:19:51,332
The jigsaw grows from the thought of the neighbor's dogs growling into thoughts like, are they going to start fighting?

141
00:19:52,074 --> 00:19:53,435
Why do they keep two dogs?

142
00:19:54,257 --> 00:19:55,117
What should I do?

143
00:19:56,460 --> 00:20:01,086
The string of thoughts based on that initial perception growling are now besetting me.

144
00:20:02,348 --> 00:20:07,355
I fitted so many jigsaw pieces together that I'm encaged by my own creation.

145
00:20:10,019 --> 00:20:13,963
This process of mental proliferation is termed Papancha in Pali.

146
00:20:15,105 --> 00:20:16,946
That's what this Sutta is addressing.

147
00:20:17,887 --> 00:20:19,710
The endless chatter of the mind.

148
00:20:20,830 --> 00:20:28,440
The way it complicates any simple idea, elaborates on it, examines it for defects and builds a world around it.

149
00:20:29,701 --> 00:20:34,406
The way it fixates on an idea and projects a happy future around that.

150
00:20:35,482 --> 00:20:38,746
the enmity it projects onto whatever gets in the way of that idea.

151
00:20:40,048 --> 00:20:42,789
This is the source of all our quarrels with the world.

152
00:20:44,271 --> 00:20:45,833
But all is not lost.

153
00:20:47,915 --> 00:20:56,124
Even though we're trapped within our monstrous jigsaw, we can train ourselves to see that we're making and remaking the jigsaw moment after moment.

154
00:20:57,365 --> 00:21:00,208
Maha Kakana assures us of this when he states,

155
00:21:01,386 --> 00:21:23,951
When there is the I, a form, and I-consciousness, it is possible to point out the manifestation of contact, and so on until When there is the manifestation of thinking, it is possible to point out the manifestation of being beset by perceptions and notions tinged by mental proliferation.

156
00:21:25,805 --> 00:21:29,388
It's the last statement which we spend most of our time working through.

157
00:21:30,411 --> 00:21:36,057
Being beset by perceptions and notions tinged by mental proliferation.

158
00:21:38,519 --> 00:21:50,714
For those of you who, like me, are impatient to get to those intriguing links between consciousness and contact, contact and feeling, I offer this analogy.

159
00:21:52,248 --> 00:21:59,336
Imagine the honey ball has a very sweet centre but is encased in a thick hard crust.

160
00:21:59,356 --> 00:22:05,224
We have to patiently nibble away at the crust before we can taste the sweet fruit at the centre.

161
00:22:07,107 --> 00:22:15,858
Can we find in the thinking process the sense of being beset by perceptions and notions tinged by mental proliferation?

162
00:22:17,492 --> 00:22:26,470
To go back to my experience of fretting about the neighbourhood dogs, if I had stopped to ask myself, are these thoughts making me happy?

163
00:22:27,592 --> 00:22:29,655
I would have had to admit that they were not.

164
00:22:31,179 --> 00:22:34,404
Why then do I keep thinking these anxious thoughts?

165
00:22:35,211 --> 00:22:38,436
The answer is that I feel compelled to think them.

166
00:22:39,298 --> 00:22:44,345
They seem important, as if the act of thinking will protect me from harm.

167
00:22:45,707 --> 00:22:49,952
So the description of being beset by my own thoughts is apt.

168
00:22:52,557 --> 00:23:01,809
When we notice thoughts in Vipassana and acknowledge that compulsion to keep thinking, we are nibbling at the hard crust of Mahakakana's honey ball.

169
00:23:03,123 --> 00:23:21,690
If I become aware of the thought stream about the neighbours' dogs and bring attention to the moment-to-moment experience, I will sense myself insisting on my point of view, that the dogs are growling, that this is a problem, that something awful might happen, and so on.

170
00:23:22,611 --> 00:23:25,434
These are the perceptions and notions that are besetting me.

171
00:23:27,237 --> 00:23:33,631
The practice, as we know, is to bring attention to the body, letting the thoughts come and go without latching onto them.

172
00:23:34,152 --> 00:23:43,692
The growling sounds, my basic point of contact in the world, might seem distant, behind an impenetrable barrier, inaccessible.

173
00:23:44,804 --> 00:23:49,691
It's as if there's an explosion of energy keeping me away from that basic sense contact.

174
00:23:50,152 --> 00:23:59,046
I feel frightened, fragmented, in my head, separate from my bodily experience, from hearing and all sense contact.

175
00:24:00,567 --> 00:24:10,423
This is hardly surprising, as the self I believe myself to be is just one piece of the jigsaw being created from these perceptual feedback loops.

176
00:24:12,547 --> 00:24:19,381
For example, the thought, this is a problem I need to fix, could be very true and pressing.

177
00:24:20,523 --> 00:24:22,327
How is the thought experienced?

178
00:24:23,690 --> 00:24:31,145
Sometimes thoughts seem very light and fleeting and an analogy often used is that of clouds passing through the sky.

179
00:24:32,527 --> 00:24:38,414
But as I attempt to look at a very pressing thought like this, the cloud refuses to pass by.

180
00:24:38,474 --> 00:24:41,098
Instead, it envelops me.

181
00:24:41,920 --> 00:24:43,702
My mind fixates around it.

182
00:24:44,703 --> 00:24:45,786
It becomes gospel.

183
00:24:47,448 --> 00:24:54,518
It's as if myself and the thought are enclosed within a bright bubble, defending ourselves against a hostile world.

184
00:24:56,978 --> 00:25:02,486
It's a very uncomfortable experience, both physically and mentally, being stuck in this bubble.

185
00:25:03,768 --> 00:25:12,038
As I let attention dwell on the experience, the bubble starts to dissolve and emotions like anger or sadness may emerge.

186
00:25:13,481 --> 00:25:16,405
Various components of the thought come more to the fore.

187
00:25:17,847 --> 00:25:20,791
At one stage, it may be the concept problem.

188
00:25:21,833 --> 00:25:25,077
I might feel myself insisting that there really is a problem.

189
00:25:25,987 --> 00:25:33,415
At another stage the notion, I need, might become predominant as I feel the anxiety behind neediness.

190
00:25:34,457 --> 00:25:42,105
Or it could be the notion, fix, that looms large in imagination as I feel myself grasping after a perfect world.

191
00:25:44,628 --> 00:25:54,339
At this stage I can acknowledge the truth of what Maha Kakana says about being beset by perceptions and notions tinged by mental proliferation.

192
00:25:55,383 --> 00:26:01,449
Notions like fix and need have my life history of self-chatter embedded within them.

193
00:26:03,130 --> 00:26:13,539
Every time I repeat a thought like, I need to do this or get that, I'm adding to the pressure inside all future thought bubbles with the phrase, I need.

194
00:26:15,422 --> 00:26:23,449
Whenever I paint a picture of how rosy the world will be once I get this or that right, I'm also adding to this pressure.

195
00:26:24,137 --> 00:26:33,099
The notions need and fix and all other components of the thought are like landmines I create by mental proliferation.

196
00:26:34,604 --> 00:26:40,137
They lie waiting in consciousness till tread upon by some innocent bit of sense contact.

197
00:26:42,515 --> 00:27:04,284
This is what the Buddha was pointing to when he explained, Bhikkhu, as to the source by which perceptions and notions tinged by mental proliferation beset a man, if nothing is found there to delight in, welcome and hold to, this is the end of the underlying tendency to lust, aversion and so on.

198
00:27:06,046 --> 00:27:11,272
It is the fact that we delight in mental chatter that causes all our problems.

199
00:27:11,792 --> 00:27:17,364
Each chat solidifies our hold on whatever notions and perceptions underlie it.

200
00:27:18,826 --> 00:27:26,422
Notions like, this is a problem and its partner, I must fix this, would be favourites for most of us.

201
00:27:27,744 --> 00:27:33,075
You could probably name your own top ten notions which underlie most of your internal chatter.

202
00:27:35,688 --> 00:27:42,499
We do, however, get moments when the emotional turmoil burns out and we feel less beset by thoughts.

203
00:27:43,681 --> 00:27:57,222
Instead of just saying, phew, I'm glad that's over and drifting into a dreamy state of relief, we can maintain our investigative stance and see can we tease out any deeper nourishment from our honey ball.

204
00:27:59,583 --> 00:28:05,069
Can we look at the process of thinking from this calmer perspective to see how it comes about?

205
00:28:06,332 --> 00:28:10,856
Can we detect the desire to link perceptions together to form thoughts?

206
00:28:13,240 --> 00:28:24,595
In my experience, perceptions are accompanied by a bright bubble of light in my mind and I get a little pop of satisfaction when a small mental bubble merges with another one.

207
00:28:25,080 --> 00:28:30,489
What was a vague notion now becomes more defined and the sense of self more solid.

208
00:28:31,790 --> 00:28:33,933
This is to study Mahakakana's statement.

209
00:28:34,776 --> 00:28:40,724
With the manifestation of perception, it is possible to point out the manifestation of thought.

210
00:28:42,606 --> 00:28:48,076
If I watch carefully, I'll notice that the pop of satisfaction is short-lived.

211
00:28:48,957 --> 00:28:50,419
The bubbles keep deflating.

212
00:28:51,480 --> 00:28:53,703
The sense of certainty dissolves with them.

213
00:28:55,000 --> 00:29:06,854
Seeing this over and over persuades me to resist the urge towards certainty and definition, to try to make peace with a world that is constantly changing, undefinable.

214
00:29:09,236 --> 00:29:14,082
Many emotions may surface as I come to terms with truth in this exercise.

215
00:29:14,803 --> 00:29:18,527
Grief, anger, fear, shame.

216
00:29:19,856 --> 00:29:33,280
But the draw towards truth holds the inquiring mind in situ, and faith helps me relax deeper into the experience, trusting that the path to peace is being formed as I bear with these emotions.

217
00:29:35,846 --> 00:29:39,451
Say, for example, I identify my emotional state as fear.

218
00:29:41,001 --> 00:29:46,213
Bringing attention to the body, I register unpleasant physical sensations and tensions.

219
00:29:47,497 --> 00:29:58,722
Alongside these, I might detect pulses of intense fear which push a description of what's happening into my head, insisting that the situation is horrid.

220
00:29:59,227 --> 00:30:04,454
What I'm experiencing according to Mahākākāna is the manifestation of perception.

221
00:30:05,797 --> 00:30:12,727
When there is the manifestation of feeling, it is possible to point out the manifestation of perception.

222
00:30:15,191 --> 00:30:26,667
Unpleasant feelings are there as a background and those little pushing sensations, the fleeting insistence that the situation is horrid, are momentary manifestations of perception.

223
00:30:27,896 --> 00:30:31,682
my mind splits itself off from what is thought of as horrid.

224
00:30:34,227 --> 00:30:41,156
In time, though, my psyche relaxes from this insistence and attention dwells more continuously in the body.

225
00:30:42,920 --> 00:30:50,811
Although the sensations haven't changed, if I had to describe them, I might call them rough, pinching, jagged, stinging.

226
00:30:52,314 --> 00:30:54,698
But these labels no longer seem relevant.

227
00:30:55,858 --> 00:31:01,525
The mind stops bothering to categorise experience, to take meaning from it, to complicate it.

228
00:31:02,846 --> 00:31:04,367
It lets the roughness be rough.

229
00:31:05,409 --> 00:31:07,551
It lets the stinging sensations sting.

230
00:31:09,554 --> 00:31:25,730
Although these are still recognised as unpleasant, feeling them fully like this is less stressful than the continual popping of mental bubbles and the effort to separate off from experience to find myself as somehow outside of it all.

231
00:31:28,630 --> 00:31:38,703
Sometimes this less stressful experience is so puzzling that it brings up the deeper fear of living in a world I cannot comprehend.

232
00:31:38,763 --> 00:31:48,376
But if conditions are right, I'll be able to trust to this unusual view of experience and start to make sense of it.

233
00:31:49,740 --> 00:32:00,192
I'll notice that the decreased stress is due to the fact that my interpretation of reality isn't centred around the notion of being a separate person.

234
00:32:01,973 --> 00:32:10,682
Sensations and feelings are known, felt, but there's no interpretation of these as happening to some entity called me.

235
00:32:12,203 --> 00:32:14,787
They're just coming and going of their own accord.

236
00:32:16,285 --> 00:32:22,635
The knowing of them is not centred around any point where I usually locate me, the knower.

237
00:32:24,579 --> 00:32:30,529
Its origin and extent are outside of experience, beyond the range of perception.

238
00:32:32,693 --> 00:32:40,587
Acknowledging the vast unknown within which my small world spins brings a deep sense of peace.

239
00:32:43,993 --> 00:32:48,434
Linked to this, we have the final part of Mahakakana's teaching.

240
00:32:49,748 --> 00:32:59,398
When there is no I, no form and no I consciousness, it is impossible to point out the manifestation of contact.

241
00:33:00,401 --> 00:33:14,237
And so on until, when there is no manifestation of thinking, it is impossible to point out the manifestation of being beset by perceptions and notions tinged by mental proliferation.

242
00:33:16,394 --> 00:33:25,487
This parallels the Buddha's advice from the Satipatthana Sutta when he asks us to notice the mind without lust, the mind without hate and so on.

243
00:33:26,848 --> 00:33:29,172
We are to notice what is not happening.

244
00:33:30,493 --> 00:33:34,420
This is not usually our habit but a very rich practice indeed.

245
00:33:37,031 --> 00:33:49,227
Again, we have to start by nibbling at the outer crust of this honey ball, acknowledging times when our minds are not beset by perceptions and notions tinged by mental proliferation.

246
00:33:51,229 --> 00:34:04,525
Whenever you feel yourself somewhat calm, interested in the sensations of breathing or walking for example, acknowledge how the absence of thought is contributing to that sense of calm.

247
00:34:07,238 --> 00:34:08,219
A word of warning.

248
00:34:09,101 --> 00:34:11,125
Absences can be hard to acknowledge.

249
00:34:12,847 --> 00:34:22,204
It is said that nature abhors a vacuum and as soon as the mind notices an absence it tends to fill it with lots of thoughts.

250
00:34:23,527 --> 00:34:24,389
No need to worry.

251
00:34:25,230 --> 00:34:27,795
This is part of the purification process.

252
00:34:29,648 --> 00:34:34,414
It's a manifestation of our fear of living in a world we cannot fully comprehend.

253
00:34:35,856 --> 00:34:39,702
Rather than work through that fear, we attach ourselves to thought.

254
00:34:40,802 --> 00:34:42,885
We even love thinking about our woes.

255
00:34:44,547 --> 00:34:50,096
What would become of us if we couldn't remember our failings and regrets, our disappointments and our worries?

256
00:34:52,398 --> 00:34:59,367
When that gets too much, we change tack and start thinking out new plans, new strategies for making ourselves happy.

257
00:35:00,715 --> 00:35:08,766
These and other mental habits often surge in to fill the gap we notice at that blessed moment of not being beset by our thoughts.

258
00:35:12,690 --> 00:35:26,688
Bearing with this and reflecting on the possibility, and occasional reality, of not thinking, loosens our attachment to these stories, encourages us to live a more embodied life,

259
00:35:28,525 --> 00:35:47,664
In deeper meditations we may get the chance to study the other absences Maha Kakana mentions and see that thoughts cannot form without perception, that perceptions only form when there is feeling and in the absence of sense contact that feelings cannot form.

260
00:35:49,179 --> 00:36:01,480
At the most profound level we might even get a glimpse of sense contact emerging as we bring attention into one or other of the sense doors to detect a signal from the outside world.

261
00:36:06,047 --> 00:36:09,333
At one level the exercise seems academic.

262
00:36:10,655 --> 00:36:15,103
Who cares whether feelings can only register based on sense contact?

263
00:36:16,213 --> 00:36:19,358
How does that help me cope with the challenges in life?

264
00:36:22,762 --> 00:36:26,907
One answer to this is that the exercise itself is purifying.

265
00:36:29,472 --> 00:36:38,643
Contemplating the possibility of living for even a moment without perception shows us how deeply attached we are to our way of seeing the world.

266
00:36:40,514 --> 00:36:50,851
We purify ourselves as we bear with the pain of attachment, the anger and grief that shows up as our minds probe this border to our understanding.

267
00:36:54,297 --> 00:36:57,543
But do remember that there's nothing wrong with perception.

268
00:36:58,485 --> 00:37:00,487
It's a vital part of our intelligence.

269
00:37:01,829 --> 00:37:05,255
It's only attachment to perception that does the damage.

270
00:37:07,007 --> 00:37:14,860
When we dare to let go of needing to always see things my way we slide into a mysterious harmony.

271
00:37:16,862 --> 00:37:22,271
Our being is content and at ease as within an indescribable universe.

272
00:37:24,393 --> 00:37:31,985
We lose our desire to describe ourselves in any way that can be contained within the phenomenal world.

273
00:37:36,978 --> 00:37:44,114
These moments also help us understand the Buddha's somewhat puzzling phrase in his address to Dandapani.

274
00:37:45,458 --> 00:37:51,813
Perceptions do not underlie the Brahmin who abides detached from sensual pleasures.

275
00:37:53,920 --> 00:38:09,324
In these moments of peace we are experiencing a fluid world where categories like this and that are not absolute but changing, dissolving, reforming in line with the constantly changing sensory stream.

276
00:38:11,246 --> 00:38:20,181
The sense of me is not defined by our present mood or our roles or by any measure we can make of our skills or behaviour.

277
00:38:21,898 --> 00:38:24,882
We don't bother defining what is indefinable.

278
00:38:26,726 --> 00:38:32,514
To use the Buddha's phrase, perceptions do not underlie our being.

279
00:38:38,923 --> 00:38:50,099
We become more willing to experience life at the level of sensation and feeling and may even see how these come into being moment after moment.

280
00:38:51,902 --> 00:39:02,340
The beauty of this simple, fluid level of reality shows us that our dreams and worries are irrelevant, burdensome, unskillful.

281
00:39:04,804 --> 00:39:10,114
Although these moments of deep insight are only temporary, they give us hope.

282
00:39:11,983 --> 00:39:29,840
Our faith in the Dharma is strengthened and when the self comes back to impose its will on the world, it is not quite so dictatorial, more ready to listen, to negotiate, to appreciate the kindness and wisdom on offer from the world.

283
00:39:32,150 --> 00:39:43,365
With a lighter heart we can pass over many grievances and see the wisdom of accepting the imperfections of the world, working with people, not against them.

284
00:39:44,947 --> 00:39:57,887
Eventually the Buddha assures us we will come to the end of quarrels, brawls, disputes, recrimination, malice and false speech.

285
00:39:59,385 --> 00:40:04,494
Here these evil, unwholesome states cease without remainder.

286
00:40:08,679 --> 00:40:15,871
In summary then, the Honeyball Sutta describes the Dhamma in terms of its ultimate goal of perfect peace.

287
00:40:18,014 --> 00:40:22,221
This is a broad-sweep overview of the Buddha's vision for his followers.

288
00:40:24,512 --> 00:40:41,268
The Sutta also pinpoints why we don't experience this peace describing how we delight in and attach to our perceptions and especially the perception of ourselves as a separate substantial entity at the centre of our world.

289
00:40:44,010 --> 00:40:54,519
Attachment to perception leads on to thoughts which eventually weave a net to ensnare us within a painful, confining world of self-definition

290
00:40:56,947 --> 00:41:14,610
The ultimate peace comes when we no longer attach to perceptions, no longer get fooled into finding our essence within anything that can be pinpointed, named, defined or in any way bound within the confines of the mind and body.

291
00:41:18,175 --> 00:41:20,980
So let's use our meditation time wisely.

292
00:41:22,039 --> 00:41:27,365
Now and again we might be troubled by the barking of the dogs nearby or other sounds.

293
00:41:28,807 --> 00:41:31,090
Can we feel any underlying emotions?

294
00:41:32,351 --> 00:41:34,693
Can we feel the urge to papantia?

295
00:41:35,735 --> 00:41:43,744
To embroider and complicate every idea, go over and back on it, defend its flaws, embellish our point of view.

296
00:41:45,827 --> 00:41:50,291
Can we sense how we create a world out of all this papantia?

297
00:41:53,224 --> 00:42:07,355
Similarly, if you're captivated by the dragonflies hovering over the pond, can you detect the urge to amplify the experience, to tell someone about it, to dig a pond in your own garden?

298
00:42:07,414 --> 00:42:13,849
Does all this thinking add to the beauty of the experience or detract from it?

299
00:42:17,204 --> 00:42:21,429
In moments of ease, can we acknowledge the absence of thinking?

300
00:42:22,389 --> 00:42:26,554
Can we see how perceptions fade as clinging is released?

301
00:42:27,817 --> 00:42:33,103
Can we detect the peace on offer when we are not blowing up so many mental bubbles?

302
00:42:34,063 --> 00:42:36,467
Is that peace founded upon perception?

303
00:42:37,648 --> 00:42:38,289
Is it mine?

304
00:42:38,349 --> 00:42:40,831
Is there even a me?

305
00:42:43,259 --> 00:42:51,835
May our meditation help us to break through the tough crust of Hapansha and be nourished by the honey ball of the Dhamma.

